<h1>BriaCell Bria-ABC Phase 3: 144-Death Event-Accrual Monte Carlo Report</h1>
<div class="meta">Prepared: 28 June 2026 · Model as-of date: 26 June 2026 · Language: English · Purpose: clinical event-timing analysis; not investment advice, medical advice, or a regulatory prediction.</div>

<h2>Executive summary</h2>
<div class="summary">
<p>This report constructs an enrollment-adjusted Monte Carlo event-accrual model to estimate when BriaCell's Bria-ABC Phase 3 trial may reach the interim threshold of <strong>144 patient events, defined as deaths</strong>. The model uses reconstructed patient entry dates, accelerating enrollment assumptions, and arm-specific overall-survival distributions.</p>
<p><strong>Main result:</strong> under the base accelerating enrollment assumption, if Bria-IMT+CPI is inactive and both main arms behave like standard therapy, the median date of the 144th death is <span class="kpi">05 Dec 2026</span>. Under a Phase 1/2-consistent Bria survival-effect scenario, the median date shifts to <span class="kpi">11 Feb 2027</span>. The difference is approximately <span class="kpi">68 days</span>, or about <span class="kpi">2.2 months</span>.</p>
<p>The limited size of this calendar shift is expected: the 144 events do not come only from the active treatment arm. They accrue across the Bria-IMT+CPI and physician's choice/TPC arms combined, while the TPC arm continues to generate deaths relatively quickly.</p>
</div>

<div class="cards">
