<h2>3. Survival distributions</h2>
<p>The simulation uses two main families of survival assumptions:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>HR=1 / inactive-drug scenario:</strong> Bria-IMT+CPI and TPC share the same standard-therapy survival distribution. Median OS sub-scenarios are 7, 9, and 11 months.</li>
<li><strong>Phase 1/2-consistent Bria-effect scenario:</strong> the TPC control arm is held around 9-11 months, while the Bria-IMT+CPI arm is assigned median OS values in the 14-17.3 month range derived from BriaCell's Phase 1/2 survival disclosures.</li>
</ul>
<p>The main survival distribution is exponential: <code>lambda = ln(2) / median OS</code>. This is a transparent starting assumption for event-accrual modeling when public data provide median OS estimates but not patient-level Kaplan-Meier curves. A future robustness layer should add Weibull shape sensitivities at 0.85, 1.00, and 1.15.</p>

<h2>4. Monte Carlo simulation design</h2>
<ul>
<li>Each patient's <code>entry_date</code> is fixed and comes from the reconstructed enrollment schedule.</li>
<li>Each patient is assigned to Bria-IMT+CPI or TPC using balanced 1:1 allocation.</li>
<li>Each patient receives a scenario-specific median OS and monthly hazard.</li>
<li>Survival time is drawn from the exponential distribution, and <code>death_date = entry_date + survival time</code>.</li>
<li>Death dates are sorted, and the 144th death date is stored in each iteration.</li>
<li>Each scenario is run with <strong>50,000 Monte Carlo replications</strong>.</li>
</ul>

