<h2>6. Enrollment-acceleration sensitivity</h2>
<p>Continued acceleration in patient enrollment pulls the 144th-death date forward, but only modestly. Newly enrolled patients expand the risk set, but they also require follow-up time before producing events. Therefore, accelerating enrollment keeps the HR=1 base scenario centered around December 2026, while the Phase 1/2-consistent Bria-effect scenario remains centered around February 2027.</p>
<div class="figure"><img src="data:image/png;base64,"><div class="caption">Figure 5. Median 144th-death dates under accelerating enrollment scenarios for the two core survival cases.</div></div>

<h2>7. Clinical and analytical interpretation</h2>
<p><strong>If the drug is inactive:</strong> in the base accelerating enrollment and HR=1 9/9-month scenario, the median date for the 144th death is <strong>05 Dec 2026</strong>. This can be used as an inactive-drug event-accrual reference line.</p>
<p><strong>If the Phase 1/2 signal is real:</strong> when the Bria-IMT+CPI arm is modeled at 16.5 months median OS and the TPC arm at 9 months, the median 144th-death date becomes <strong>11 Feb 2027</strong>. This is an approximately <strong>2.2-month delay</strong>.</p>
<p>This delay may look small, but it is consistent with event-driven trial mechanics. The 144 deaths accrue across both main arms, not only from the Bria arm. Because the TPC arm continues to generate events quickly, a meaningful survival extension in the active arm translates into a limited but potentially informative calendar delay.</p>
<div class="note"><strong>Interpretation boundary:</strong> a delay beyond the HR=1 event-accrual reference is not, by itself, proof of efficacy. However, if enrollment, analysis-set, and reporting-lag assumptions are approximately correct, a sustained delay would be directionally consistent with longer-than-expected survival in the Bria-IMT+CPI arm.</div>

<h2>8. Limitations and recommended robustness layer</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>No full SAP/protocol:</strong> excluding monotherapy is based on public source language; an all-randomized sensitivity analysis should be added.</li>
<li><strong>"Over 230" uncertainty:</strong> 230 is treated as a conservative lower bound; alternative May 2026 baselines such as 240 or 250 should be tested.</li>
<li><strong>No patient-level profile data:</strong> subtype, ECOG status, age, HLA matching, and prior-line counts are not known at patient level; survival is modeled by arm and scenario.</li>
<li><strong>Distribution sensitivity:</strong> exponential is the main model; Weibull shapes of 0.85 and 1.15 should test early-risk and rising-risk alternatives.</li>
<li><strong>Announcement lag:</strong> the simulation estimates the true date on which the 144th death occurs. Public topline disclosure may lag by 30-60 days or more due to data cutoff, validation, database lock, DSMB review, and analysis.</li>
</ul>

